{"title_page": "Letters of last resort", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Short description|United Kingdom letters regarding strategy in the event of a nuclear attack on its government}}[[File:HMS VIGILANT MOD 45137620.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The United Kingdom relies on four [[Vanguard-class submarine|''Vanguard''-class submarines]] ({{HMS|Vigilant|S30|6}} pictured) to provide its nuclear deterrent. At least one submarine is always armed and on active service, carrying up to 16 [[Trident II]] [[submarine-launched ballistic missile]]s. Each missile has a range of 7000 miles (11,000&nbsp;km), and can carry 12 independently controlled warheads each capable of destroying a large city.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Brown move to cut UK nuclear subs |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8270092.stm |publisher= BBC News |date=23 September 2009 |accessdate=24 January 2011}}</ref> ]]\n\nThe '''letters of last resort''' are four identically worded handwritten letters from the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] to the commanding officers of the four [[Vanguard-class submarine|British ballistic missile submarines]]. They contain orders on what action to take in the event that an enemy [[nuclear strike]] has destroyed the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] and has killed or otherwise incapacitated both the prime minister and the \"second person\" (normally a high-ranking member of [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|the Cabinet]], such as the [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]] or the [[First Secretary of State]]) whom the prime minister has designated to make a decision on how to act in the event of the prime minister's death. In the event that the orders are carried out, the action taken could be the last official act of the [[Government of the United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"Taylor 2016\">{{cite web | title=Every new British prime minister pens a handwritten \u2018letter of last resort\u2019 outlining nuclear retaliation | website=Washington Post | date=13 July 2016 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/07/13/every-new-british-prime-minister-pens-a-hand-written-letter-of-last-resort-outlining-nuclear-retaliaton/ | accessdate=13 July 2016 | last=Taylor | first=Adam}}</ref>\n\nThe letters are stored inside two nested safes in the control room of each submarine.<ref>{{Cite journal|last= Rosenbaum |first= Ron | authorlink= |author2= |date=January 2009 |title=The Letter of Last Resort |journal=Slate Magazine |volume= | issue = |pages= |id= |url= http://www.slate.com/id/2208219 |accessdate= 18 May 2009 |quote= In the control room of the sub, the Daily Mail reports, \"there is a safe attached to a control room floor. Inside that, there is an inner safe. And inside that sits a letter. It is addressed to the submarine commander and it is from the Prime Minister.}}</ref> The letters are destroyed unopened after a prime minister leaves office, so their content remains known only to the prime minister who issued them.<ref>{{Cite journal|last= Rosenbaum |first= Ron | authorlink= |author2= |date=January 2009 |title=The Letter of Last Resort |journal=Slate Magazine |volume= | issue = |pages= |id= |url= http://www.slate.com/id/2208219 |accessdate= 18 March 2012 |quote= [E]very prime minister in recent years has written such a letter and ... letters that go unused (Tony Blair's for instance) are destroyed without being read.}}</ref>\n\n==Process==\nThe letters are written as soon as a new prime minister takes office, after they have been told by the [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]] \"precisely what damage a [[Trident missile]] could cause\".<ref name=\"Norton-Taylor 2016\">{{cite web | last=Norton-Taylor | first=Richard | title=Theresa May's first job: decide on UK's nuclear response | website=the Guardian | date=11 July 2016 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/12/theresa-mays-first-job-decide-on-uks-nuclear-response | accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref> These are then delivered to the submarines, with the previous prime minister's letters being destroyed without being opened.<ref name=\"Bunkall 2016\">{{cite web | last=Bunkall | first=Alistair | title=May To Be Handed Keys To Nuclear Red Button | website=Sky News | date=13 July 2016 | url=http://news.sky.com/story/may-to-be-handed-keys-to-nuclear-red-button-10499943 | accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the event of the deaths of both the prime minister and the designated alternative decision-maker as a result of a nuclear strike, the commander(s) of the nuclear submarine(s) (at any time at least one is on patrol) would use a series of checks to ascertain whether the letters of last resort will have to be opened.<ref>{{cite news|title=Theresa May\u2019s grim first task: Preparing for nuclear armageddon|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/the-grim-task-awaiting-theresa-may-preparing-for-nuclear-armageddon-uk-prime-minister-british-defense-letter-of-last-resort/|accessdate=15 July 2016|work=Politico|date=15 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Peter Hennessy]]'s book ''The Secret State: Whitehall and the Cold War, 1945 to 1970'', the process by which a {{sclass-|Vanguard|submarine}} commander would determine if the British government continues to function includes, amongst other checks, establishing whether [[BBC Radio 4]] continues broadcasting.<ref>{{cite news|title=HMS Apocalypse: Deep in the Atlantic, a submarine waits on alert with nuclear missiles that would end the world...|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1090400/HMS-Apocalypse-Deep-Atlantic-submarine-waits-alert-nuclear-missiles-end-world--.html|accessdate=10 May 2012 | location=London|work=Daily Mail}}</ref><ref name=\"The Drive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/7300/letters-of-last-resort-are-post-apocalyptic-orders-for-uk-vanguard-sub-crews|title=Letters Of Last Resort Are Post-Apocalyptic Orders for UK Vanguard Sub Crews|last=Rogoway|first=Tyler|date=February 1, 2017|publisher=The Drive|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, the procedure for [[UK Polaris programme|Polaris]] submarines was to open the envelopes if there was an evident nuclear attack, or if all UK naval broadcasts had ceased for four hours.<ref>{{Citation| last= Goodall| first= David| publication-date=1 August 2013\n| date= 26 May 1983| title= Arrangements for briefing a new Prime Minister in the event of a change of administration following the 1983 General Election| publisher = [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|TNA]])|id= [[Cabinet Office|CAB]] 196/124\n|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/SearchUI/details/C13497321?uri=C13497321|accessdate=5 September 2013|format= [[PDF]]\n}}</ref>\n\n==Options==\nWhile the contents of these letters are secret, according to the December 2008 BBC Radio 4 documentary ''The Human Button'', there were four known options given to the prime minister to include in the letters.  The prime minister might instruct the submarine commander to:\n\n* retaliate with [[nuclear weapon]]s;\n* not retaliate;\n* use his or her own judgement; or\n* place the submarine under an allied country's command, if possible.  The documentary mentions Australia and the United States.\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' reported in 2016 that the options are said to include: \"Put yourself under the command of the US, if it is still there\", \"Go to Australia\", \"Retaliate\", or \"Use your own judgement\".<ref name=\"Norton-Taylor 2016\" />\n\nThe actual option chosen remains known only to the writer of the letter, as they are destroyed unopened when a prime minister leaves office.\n\n==Fiction==\n[[David Greig (dramatist)|David Greig]]'s 2012 play ''The Letter of Last Resort'' deals with the consequences and paradoxes of the letters.<ref>[[David Greig (dramatist)|David Greig]], ''[http://www.front-step.co.uk/2015/09/30/letter-of-last-resort/ The Letter of Last Resort]'' (full text of play), front-step.co.uk (David Greig's official website), posted 30 September 2015.</ref>\n\nThe play was first staged in February 2012 as a part of a cycle of plays on \"The Bomb\" at the [[Tricycle Theatre]] in London, directed by [[Nicolas Kent]], with [[Belinda Lang]] playing the role of the incoming prime minister and [[Simon Chandler]] her advisor.<ref>[[Michael Billington (critic)|Michael Billington]], [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2012/feb/21/the-bomb-review The Bomb - review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 21 February 2012</ref> The production was also seen at the [[Traverse Theatre]] in Edinburgh, for the [[Edinburgh Fringe]] later the same year.<ref>[http://www.tricycle.co.uk/home/about-the-tricycle-pages/about-us-tab-menu/archive/archived-theatre-production/the-letter-of-last-resort/ Edinburgh Transfer: The Letter of Last Resort], [[Tricycle Theatre]], August 2012</ref>  The following year it was broadcast on [[BBC Radio 4]], with the same cast, first transmitted on 1 June 2013.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Saturday Drama, The Last Resort|work=BBC Radio 4 website|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0210spc|date=1 June 2013|accessdate=1 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe KGB's attempts to obtain the contents of the letters of last resort are part of the plot of the BBC [[Cold War]] spy drama ''[[The Game (UK TV series)|The Game]]'' (2014).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Frost |first1=Vicky |title=The Game recap: series one, episode two \u2013 Operation Glass is revealed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2015/may/07/the-game-recap-series-one-episode-two-operation-glass-is-revealed |accessdate=14 November 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=7 May 2015 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Operation Looking Glass]]\n* [[Dead Hand]]\n* [[Mutually assured destruction]]\n* [[Nuclear weapons and the United Kingdom#Nuclear weapons control|Nuclear weapons and the United Kingdom \u00a7 Nuclear weapons control]]\n* [[Trident nuclear programme]]\n* [[Fail-deadly]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite news|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1090400/HMS-Apocalypse-Deep-Atlantic-submarine-waits-alert-nuclear-missiles-end-world--.html|title = HMAS Apocalypse: Deep in the Atlantic, a submarine waits on alert with nuclear missiles that would end the world...|last = Hennessy|first = Peter|date = 30 November 2008|access-date = 10 February 2015|last2 = Knight|first2 = Richard|newspaper = Daily Mail}}\n* {{Cite web|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/pip/fseue/|title = The Human Button|date = 2 December 2008|accessdate = 10 February 2015|website = BBC Radio 4}}\n* {{Cite news|url = http://www.slate.com/articles/life/the_spectator/2009/01/the_letter_of_last_resort.single.html|title = The Letter of Last Resort|last = Rosenbaum|first = Ron|date = 9 January 2009|work = Slate|access-date = 10 February 2015}}\n* Radio archive: {{Cite web|url = http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/399/Contents-Unknown?bypass=true|title = 399: Contents Unknown (Prologue)|date = 22 January 2010|accessdate = 10 February 2015|website = This American Life|last = Glass|first = Ira}}\n\n[[Category:Cabinet Office (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Emergency management in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Letters (message)]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom nuclear command and control]]\n[[Category:Nuclear strategy]]\n[[Category:Nuclear secrecy]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Short description|United Kingdom letters regarding strategy in the event of a nuclear attack on its government}}[[File:HMS VIGILANT MOD 45137620.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The United Kingdom relies on four [[Vanguard-class submarine|''Vanguard''-class submarines]] ({{HMS|Vigilant|S30|6}} pictured) to provide its nuclear deterrent. At least one submarine is always armed and on active service, carrying up to 16 [[Trident II]] [[submarine-launched ballistic missile]]s. Each missile has a range of 7000 miles (11,000&nbsp;km), and can carry 12 independently controlled warheads each capable of destroying a large city.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Brown move to cut UK nuclear subs |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8270092.stm |publisher= BBC News |date=23 September 2009 |accessdate=24 January 2011}}</ref> ]]\n\nThe '''letters of last resort''' are four identically worded handwritten letters from the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] to the commanding officers of the four [[Vanguard-class submarine|British ballistic missile submarines]]. They contain orders on what action to take in the event that an enemy [[nuclear strike]] has destroyed the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] and has killed or otherwise incapacitated both the prime minister and the \"second person\" (normally a high-ranking member of [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|the Cabinet]], such as the [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]] or the [[First Secretary of State]]) whom the prime minister has designated to make a decision on how to act in the event of the prime minister's death. In the event that the orders are carried out, the action taken could be the last official act of [[Government of the United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"Taylor 2016\">{{cite web | title=Every new British prime minister pens a handwritten \u2018letter of last resort\u2019 outlining nuclear retaliation | website=Washington Post | date=13 July 2016 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/07/13/every-new-british-prime-minister-pens-a-hand-written-letter-of-last-resort-outlining-nuclear-retaliaton/ | accessdate=13 July 2016 | last=Taylor | first=Adam}}</ref>\n\nThe letters are stored inside two nested safes in the control room of each submarine.<ref>{{Cite journal|last= Rosenbaum |first= Ron | authorlink= |author2= |date=January 2009 |title=The Letter of Last Resort |journal=Slate Magazine |volume= | issue = |pages= |id= |url= http://www.slate.com/id/2208219 |accessdate= 18 May 2009 |quote= In the control room of the sub, the Daily Mail reports, \"there is a safe attached to a control room floor. Inside that, there is an inner safe. And inside that sits a letter. It is addressed to the submarine commander and it is from the Prime Minister.}}</ref> The letters are destroyed unopened after a prime minister leaves office, so their content remains known only to the prime minister who issued them.<ref>{{Cite journal|last= Rosenbaum |first= Ron | authorlink= |author2= |date=January 2009 |title=The Letter of Last Resort |journal=Slate Magazine |volume= | issue = |pages= |id= |url= http://www.slate.com/id/2208219 |accessdate= 18 March 2012 |quote= [E]very prime minister in recent years has written such a letter and ... letters that go unused (Tony Blair's for instance) are destroyed without being read.}}</ref>\n\n==Process==\nThe letters are written as soon as a new prime minister takes office, after they have been told by the [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]] \"precisely what damage a [[Trident missile]] could cause\".<ref name=\"Norton-Taylor 2016\">{{cite web | last=Norton-Taylor | first=Richard | title=Theresa May's first job: decide on UK's nuclear response | website=the Guardian | date=11 July 2016 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/12/theresa-mays-first-job-decide-on-uks-nuclear-response | accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref> These are then delivered to the submarines, with the previous prime minister's letters being destroyed without being opened.<ref name=\"Bunkall 2016\">{{cite web | last=Bunkall | first=Alistair | title=May To Be Handed Keys To Nuclear Red Button | website=Sky News | date=13 July 2016 | url=http://news.sky.com/story/may-to-be-handed-keys-to-nuclear-red-button-10499943 | accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the event of the deaths of both the prime minister and the designated alternative decision-maker as a result of a nuclear strike, the commander(s) of the nuclear submarine(s) (at any time at least one is on patrol) would use a series of checks to ascertain whether the letters of last resort will have to be opened.<ref>{{cite news|title=Theresa May\u2019s grim first task: Preparing for nuclear armageddon|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/the-grim-task-awaiting-theresa-may-preparing-for-nuclear-armageddon-uk-prime-minister-british-defense-letter-of-last-resort/|accessdate=15 July 2016|work=Politico|date=15 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Peter Hennessy]]'s book ''The Secret State: Whitehall and the Cold War, 1945 to 1970'', the process by which a {{sclass-|Vanguard|submarine}} commander would determine if the British government continues to function includes, amongst other checks, establishing whether [[BBC Radio 4]] continues broadcasting.<ref>{{cite news|title=HMS Apocalypse: Deep in the Atlantic, a submarine waits on alert with nuclear missiles that would end the world...|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1090400/HMS-Apocalypse-Deep-Atlantic-submarine-waits-alert-nuclear-missiles-end-world--.html|accessdate=10 May 2012 | location=London|work=Daily Mail}}</ref><ref name=\"The Drive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/7300/letters-of-last-resort-are-post-apocalyptic-orders-for-uk-vanguard-sub-crews|title=Letters Of Last Resort Are Post-Apocalyptic Orders for UK Vanguard Sub Crews|last=Rogoway|first=Tyler|date=February 1, 2017|publisher=The Drive|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, the procedure for [[UK Polaris programme|Polaris]] submarines was to open the envelopes if there was an evident nuclear attack, or if all UK naval broadcasts had ceased for four hours.<ref>{{Citation| last= Goodall| first= David| publication-date=1 August 2013\n| date= 26 May 1983| title= Arrangements for briefing a new Prime Minister in the event of a change of administration following the 1983 General Election| publisher = [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|TNA]])|id= [[Cabinet Office|CAB]] 196/124\n|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/SearchUI/details/C13497321?uri=C13497321|accessdate=5 September 2013|format= [[PDF]]\n}}</ref>\n\n==Options==\nWhile the contents of these letters are secret, according to the December 2008 BBC Radio 4 documentary ''The Human Button'', there were four known options given to the prime minister to include in the letters.  The prime minister might instruct the submarine commander to:\n\n* retaliate with [[nuclear weapon]]s;\n* not retaliate;\n* use his or her own judgement; or\n* place the submarine under an allied country's command, if possible.  The documentary mentions Australia and the United States.\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' reported in 2016 that the options are said to include: \"Put yourself under the command of the US, if it is still there\", \"Go to Australia\", \"Retaliate\", or \"Use your own judgement\".<ref name=\"Norton-Taylor 2016\" />\n\nThe actual option chosen remains known only to the writer of the letter, as they are destroyed unopened when a prime minister leaves office.\n\n==Fiction==\n[[David Greig (dramatist)|David Greig]]'s 2012 play ''The Letter of Last Resort'' deals with the consequences and paradoxes of the letters.<ref>[[David Greig (dramatist)|David Greig]], ''[http://www.front-step.co.uk/2015/09/30/letter-of-last-resort/ The Letter of Last Resort]'' (full text of play), front-step.co.uk (David Greig's official website), posted 30 September 2015.</ref>\n\nThe play was first staged in February 2012 as a part of a cycle of plays on \"The Bomb\" at the [[Tricycle Theatre]] in London, directed by [[Nicolas Kent]], with [[Belinda Lang]] playing the role of the incoming prime minister and [[Simon Chandler]] her advisor.<ref>[[Michael Billington (critic)|Michael Billington]], [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2012/feb/21/the-bomb-review The Bomb - review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 21 February 2012</ref> The production was also seen at the [[Traverse Theatre]] in Edinburgh, for the [[Edinburgh Fringe]] later the same year.<ref>[http://www.tricycle.co.uk/home/about-the-tricycle-pages/about-us-tab-menu/archive/archived-theatre-production/the-letter-of-last-resort/ Edinburgh Transfer: The Letter of Last Resort], [[Tricycle Theatre]], August 2012</ref>  The following year it was broadcast on [[BBC Radio 4]], with the same cast, first transmitted on 1 June 2013.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Saturday Drama, The Last Resort|work=BBC Radio 4 website|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0210spc|date=1 June 2013|accessdate=1 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe KGB's attempts to obtain the contents of the letters of last resort are part of the plot of the BBC [[Cold War]] spy drama ''[[The Game (UK TV series)|The Game]]'' (2014).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Frost |first1=Vicky |title=The Game recap: series one, episode two \u2013 Operation Glass is revealed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2015/may/07/the-game-recap-series-one-episode-two-operation-glass-is-revealed |accessdate=14 November 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=7 May 2015 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Operation Looking Glass]]\n* [[Dead Hand]]\n* [[Mutually assured destruction]]\n* [[Nuclear weapons and the United Kingdom#Nuclear weapons control|Nuclear weapons and the United Kingdom \u00a7 Nuclear weapons control]]\n* [[Trident nuclear programme]]\n* [[Fail-deadly]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite news|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1090400/HMS-Apocalypse-Deep-Atlantic-submarine-waits-alert-nuclear-missiles-end-world--.html|title = HMAS Apocalypse: Deep in the Atlantic, a submarine waits on alert with nuclear missiles that would end the world...|last = Hennessy|first = Peter|date = 30 November 2008|access-date = 10 February 2015|last2 = Knight|first2 = Richard|newspaper = Daily Mail}}\n* {{Cite web|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/pip/fseue/|title = The Human Button|date = 2 December 2008|accessdate = 10 February 2015|website = BBC Radio 4}